				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Among Polling Firms, Only One Got the Indian Elections Right</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Malavika Vyawahare			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-05-19T10:47:28+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">May 19, 2014 6:47 am</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">May 19, 2014 6:47 am</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content"><div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/05/19/world/asia/19-exit-polls-IndiaInk/19-exit-polls-IndiaInk-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/05/19/world/asia/19-exit-polls-IndiaInk/19-exit-polls-IndiaInk-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/05/19/world/asia/19-exit-polls-IndiaInk/19-exit-polls-IndiaInk-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000002888377" width="592" height="404" alt="People watching Indian election results on a screen outside the Bharatiya Janata Party office in Mumbai, Maharashtra, on Friday."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="404"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">People watching Indian election results on a screen outside the Bharatiya Janata Party office in Mumbai, Maharashtra, on Friday.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Punit Paranjpe/Agence France-Presse â Getty Images</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//india.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/05/19/among-polling-firms-only-one-got-the-indian-elections-right/" data-title="Among Polling Firms, Only One Got the Indian Elections Right" data-description="Todayâs Chanakya was the only one to predict the magnitude of both the B.J.P.âs victory and the governing Indian National Congress partyâs loss.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><br />
NEW DELHI â After the final vote was cast on May 12, exit polls pointed to a win by the opposition Bharatiya Janata Party led by its candidate for prime minister, Narendra Modi. But only one polling firm, <a href="//www.todayschanakya.com/loksabha_result_2014.html">Todayâs Chanakya</a><span style="text-decoration: underline;">, </span>predicted the magnitude of both the B.J.P.âs victory and the governing Indian National Congress partyâs loss.</p>
<div class="inlineModule"><div class="entry"><h6 class="kicker"><a href="//india.blogs.nytimes.com/category/india-votes/">India Votes</a></h6><p class="summary">News and analysis on the worldâs largest election. </p></div></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Only Todayâs Chanakya predicted that the B.J.P would exceed the 272-seat mark in the lower house of Parliament, which would allow the party to form a government on its own, without coalition partners. The polling firm projected the B.J.P. would win 291 seats out of the 543 up for grabs, with a margin of error of 14 seats either way. The B.J.P.âs final tally stood at 282 seats.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Todayâs Chanakya also predicted that the Congress party would get 57 seats, with a margin of  error of nine seats, the lowest estimate among all pollsters. The governing party won only 44 seats.<span id="more-75991"></span></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In a country where <a href="//india.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/03/05/the-problem-with-exit-polls-in-indian-elections/?_php=true&amp;_type=blogs&amp;_r=0">polling firms are unreliable</a>, Todayâs Chanakyaâs track record is impressive. Its forecasts for the Indian parliamentary elections in 2004 and 2009 were also within striking distance of the actual results. It was also the only one to predict the <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/12/09/world/asia/india-state-elections.html?pagewanted=all">stunning electoral debut</a> of the fledgling Aam Aadmi Party in the Delhi State elections in December.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Todayâs Chanakya is the political analysis arm of <a href="//www.rnbresearch.com/">RNB </a>Research, a market research firm based in Delhi that has clients across the world. It is named after a historical Indian scholar, Chanakya, who was famous for his expertise in the political economy.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The firm has conducted political research for clients, political parties, media organizations and individuals, but not all of it is in the public domain. Though V. K.<b> </b>Bajaj, the chief executive officer at Todayâs Chanakya, declined to share his data, citing client confidentiality, he said that the companyâs 2004 and 2008 United States presidential election predictions were accurate as well.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In India, Mr. Bajaj said that what makes his polling firmâs predictions more reliable than others is the pains his team takes to ensure that the polling sample is representative.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThe mantra is to get the sample right,â he said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">For the latest poll, team members interviewed 38,984 people across 22 states and two union territories, including Delhi. The data collected included age, gender, social class, household, work status and literacy level, according to the company&#8217;s website.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">What trips up most polling firms in India is the multitude of factors that affect the electoral outcomes, Mr. Bajaj said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âA U.S. or U.K. or any other national election can be predicted using a relatively small sample size, but India is more complex, Mr. Bajaj said. The caste equations play an important role, he said, and the urban-rural divide is another consideration, which differs across regions.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âAny poll conducted in the state of Uttar Pradesh will have to take into account the vast rural population, while in a place like Mumbai, the rural vote is not that important,â Mr. Bajaj said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The polling firmâs numbers for the key state of Uttar Pradesh, which sends 80 legislators to Parliament, were uncannily accurate, giving the B.J.P. a tally of about 70 seats. It won 71, more than seven times what the party Â secured in the last election in 2009.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The federal structure of the Indian polity, which divides powers between central and state governments, also complicates matters. Many political parties contest elections both at the national and state levels.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âWe need to understand how the performance of the state government will impact the partyâs fortunes in the national elections,â he said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Todayâs Chanakya has about 170 core members, with field workers hired on a temporary basis. This yearâs exit poll used about 250 field workers, Mr. Bajaj said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Because electronic methods of polling, like phone or Internet, havenât worked well in India, a largely rural country, Mr. Bajaj said his firm surveyed voters through face-to-face interviews, paper forms filled out by respondents and a method called mystery shopping, in which interviewers go into the field posing as voters and make casual talk with a potential voter to elicit responses.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âWe usually use this in areas which are sensitive or where there is some fear factor which prevents people from being open about their electoral choices,â Mr. Bajaj said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The efforts by Todayâs Chanakya to ensure it has a representative polling sample clearly pays off, especially when compared to its rivals at home. By Mr. Bajajâs own estimate, local polling companies get the results wrong half the time.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Bajaj said his company is careful to avoid personal bias; his analystsâ conclusions are based on pure data.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âPerception in India matters a lot, and sometimes researchersâ perceptions are superimposed on data,â he said.</p>
	</div>
